Jun 1 2007 	Easy access to L O'Hare and expressways	I chose this hotel for a mini-vacation over Memorial Day weekend. I wanted access to downtown Chicago's shopping, dining, and culture. The hotel is only a 5-minute walk from the Cumberland L station. That let me go downtown without worrying about auto traffic and parking. However, the Blue Line was undergoing renovation, and the trip seemed closer to an hour than the usual 45 minutes. Also, I wanted access to visit family outside the city. The hotel is barely a block or two from the Cumberland I-90 exit. In addition, I was flying out of O'Hare. I don't think it took me more than 10 minutes to drive from the hotel to the Hertz car return. So the hotel met my key expectation: convenient location.My Hertz reservation led me to a special deal for that weekend. I stayed three nights at a $109 base rate, but the special deal meant that I only had to pay for the first two nights. I'm glad I brought the Internet printout explaining the special deal. At both check-in and check-out, the clerks were unfamiliar with it. However, both times they took my printout to the manager. After a few minutes, they came back and honored the special deal. I did have to pay for wired Internet ($12.95/night) and self-parking ($16.75/night).My room was in the tower, which was close to the lobby. However, parts of the hotel are some distance away. The walk to the fitness center was roughly 5 minutes. On the way there, I noticed two men starting their workout by running through the hallway to the fitness center. That made sense since the distance was so great. The fitness center itself was uncrowded during my visits. An elliptical-type cardiovascular machine worked well and had a built-in tv; I had to bring my own headphones to listen to the sound. The center also has weight machines, and the hotel has indoor and outdoor pools.The room itself was generally typical of other Marriotts where I've stayed in size, decor, and general condition. In other words, it was adequate, with no significant problems but no especially exciting features. The king bed did seem to reflect the recent trend toward a soft, complicated set of bedding with lots of pillows. Although the hotel was close to O'Hare and I occasionally heard airplanes, I was able to sleep undisturbed by noise. I encountered uniformly friendly and helpful staff--including the bellman at the front door, the maid, and the parking lot attendant. They seemed genuinely eager to help. They lacked the stiff formality of a Ritz-Carlton, and they lacked the seemingly clairvoyant anticipation of my needs I had found at the W City Center in Chicago on an earlier trip.Overall, I was pleased with the hotel's convenient location, great rates, adequate facilities, and helpful staff.	
May 8 2007 	Suite was like a cave.	We usually stay in suites when we travel for more space to work and stretch out. We had to fly into Chicago unexpectedly due to a family emergency and as I usually stay at Marriott hotels, I did a quick search. My brother in law said the Marriott Hotel O'Hare was closest to the hospital of the hotels Marriott listed so I booked a suite at almost $250 night, plus huge tax rate and parking. I requested a top floor, expecting their suites to be on the top of their tower building. Instead they are on the third floor of the old 1970's style holiday inn building that surrounds the pools. (Which did look pretty nice). After walking what seemed like forever we walked down a musty smelling hallway, which they were carpet cleaning at the time. (really strong smell). The suite itself was an ok size, but the room has only one large plate glass window that opened to a set of stairs from the outside parking lot (no sense of security) and a walkway for access to some AMA building. Their is a huge overhang over this walkway, so natural light was almost non existent. The window and airconditioning were in the main living area, and the bed was tucked into a back corner with no window and no air vent. Freezing in the living area and hot on the bed. Go figure.The bathroom was tiny with barely enough room to turn around from the sink, toilet and worn out puny tub. The bed was saggy and lumpy and neither of us slept well. They throw a lumpy, prickly topper on the mattress and think it will account for a bad mattress.I must say that the front desk staff was very nice, but I immediately got online and booked the remainder of our stay at the Marriott Suites, which was just two minutes down the road. That is the place to stay.I hate to dish Marriott, because I am almost always happy with them, but this Marriott is not what I expected for the price and the name.	
